ansparent [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8"><div><div class="standard-markdown grid-cols-1 grid [&amp;_&gt;_*]:min-w-0 gap-3 standard-markdown"><p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">The short answer is: <strong>not fully automatic</strong>, but you can get close with some clever techniques.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">Here's the reality of iOS keyboard behavior:</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>The core limitation</strong></p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">iOS doesn't support mid-field automatic keyboard switching. The keyboard type is set per-input field (<code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">inputmode</code>, <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">type</code>, etc.), not per-character position. So a single field can't natively flip from numeric to alpha and back.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>What you CAN do</strong></p>
<ol class="[li_&amp;]:mb-0 [li_&amp;]:mt-1 [li_&amp;]:gap-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ul]:pb-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ol]:pb-1 list-decimal flex flex-col gap-1 pl-8 mb-3">
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2"><strong>Split the field into segments</strong> — The most practical approach. For <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">NN-AAA-NNNN</code> (e.g., date of birth like <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">15-JAN-2024</code>), you'd use three separate inputs:
<ul class="[li_&amp;]:mb-0 [li_&amp;]:mt-1 [li_&amp;]:gap-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ul]:pb-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ol]:pb-1 list-disc flex flex-col gap-1 pl-8 mb-3">
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Field 1: <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">inputmode="numeric"</code> → 2 digits</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Field 2: <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">inputmode="text"</code> + <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">autocomplete="off"</code> + <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">autocapitalize="characters"</code> → 3 letters</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Field 3: <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">inputmode="numeric"</code> → 4 digits</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Auto-advance focus as each segment fills up — this naturally triggers the keyboard switch.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2"><strong>Single field with a custom keyboard</strong> — Build an on-screen custom keypad in HTML/CSS/JS that overlays the native keyboard. Full control, but significant build effort and it won't feel as native.</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2"><strong>Single field, accept the friction</strong> — Use <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">inputmode="text"</code> on one field and let the user switch manually. A clear placeholder like <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">DD-MMM-YYYY</code> guides them, but they toggle the keyboard themselves.</li>
</ol>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>The auto-advance split-field approach is the gold standard</strong> — it's what apps like credit card forms use (MM / YY / CVV), and it's what users expect. The keyboard switch feels natural because it happens at the field boundary.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">Want me to build a working example of the split-field approach for your date-of-birth case?</p></div></div></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-start opacity-0 group-hover:opacity-100 group-focus-within:opacity-100 transition" role="group" aria-label="Message actions"><div class="text-text-300"><div class="text-text-300 flex items-stretch justify-between"><div class="w-fit" data-state="closed"><button class="inline-flex
