ansparent [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8"><div><div class="standard-markdown grid-cols-1 grid [&amp;_&gt;_*]:min-w-0 gap-3 standard-markdown"><p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">Great question. Yes, but with some nuances across contexts:</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>Split-field approach in desktop Chrome</strong></p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">On desktop, <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">inputmode</code> is largely ignored — it's a mobile hint. But <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">type="text"</code> with <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">pattern</code> validation works well:</p>
<ul class="[li_&amp;]:mb-0 [li_&amp;]:mt-1 [li_&amp;]:gap-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ul]:pb-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ol]:pb-1 list-disc flex flex-col gap-1 pl-8 mb-3">
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Field 1: <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">type="text" pattern="\d{2}"</code> → enforces 2 digits</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Field 2: <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">type="text" pattern="[A-Za-z]{3}"</code> → enforces 3 letters</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Field 3: <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">type="text" pattern="\d{4}"</code> → enforces 4 digits</li>
</ul>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">Chrome will show a red outline / validation message on submit if the pattern isn't met.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>The compatibility matrix</strong></p>
<div class="overflow-x-auto w-full px-2 mb-6"><table class="min-w-full border-collapse text-sm leading-[1.7] whitespace-normal"><thead class="text-left"><tr><th scope="col" class="text-text-100 border-b-0.5 border-border-300/60 py-2 pr-4 align-top font-bold">Feature</th><th scope="col" class="text-text-100 border-b-0.5 border-border-300/60 py-2 pr-4 align-top font-bold">iOS Safari</th><th scope="col" class="text-text-100 border-b-0.5 border-border-300/60 py-2 pr-4 align-top font-bold">Android Chrome</th><th scope="col" class="text-text-100 border-b-0.5 border-border-300/60 py-2 pr-4 align-top font-bold">Desktop Chrome</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class="border-b-0.5 border-border-300/30 py-2 pr-4 align-top"><code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">inputmode="numeric"</code> keyboard</td><td class="border-b-0.5 border-border-300/30 py-2 pr-4 align-top">✅</td><td class="border-b-0.5 border-border-300/30 py-2 pr-4 align-top">✅</td><td class="border-b-0.5 border-border-300/30 py-2 pr-4 align-top">ignored</td></tr><tr><td class="border-b-0.5 border-border-300/30 py-2 pr-4 align-top"><code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">pattern</code> validation on submit</td><td class="border-b-0.5 border-border-300/30 py-2 pr-4 align-top">✅</td><td class="border-b-0.5 border-border-300/30 py-2 pr-4 align-top">✅</td><td class="border-b-0.5 border-border-300/30 py-2 pr-4 align-top">✅</td></tr><tr><td class="border-b-0.5 border-border-300/30 py-2 pr-4 align-top">Auto-advance on fill</td><td class="border-b-0.5 border-border-300/30 py-2 pr-4 align-top">✅ (JS)</td><td class="border-b-0.5 border-border-300/30 py-2 pr-4 align-top">✅ (JS)</td><td class="border-b-0.5 border-border-300/30 py-2 pr-4 align-top">✅ (JS)</td></tr><tr><td class="border-b-0.5 border-border-300/30 py-2 pr-4 align-top">Native keyboard switch</td><td class="border-b-0.5 border-border-300/30 py-2 pr-4 align-top">via field boundary</td><td class="border-b-0.5 border-border-300/30 py-2 pr-4 align-top">via field boundary</td><td class="border-b-0.5 border-border-300/30 py-2 pr-4 align-top">N/A</td></tr></tbody></table></div>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>One caveat: <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">type="number"</code> vs <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">inputmode="numeric"</code></strong></p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">Avoid <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">type="number"</code> for these fields — Chrome will reject leading zeros and non-integer input, which breaks things like day <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">01</code> or month <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">JAN</code>. Stick with <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">type="text"</code> + <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">inputmode="numeric"</code> + <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">pattern="\d{N}"</code> for numeric segments.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>Bottom line</strong></p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">The split-field approach works consistently across all browsers and iOS — pattern validation satisfies Chrome's correctness checking, and <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">inputmode</code> handles the mobile keyboard switching. It's genuinely the right solution for this use case.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">Want me to build the working demo now?</p></div></div></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-start opacity-0 group-hover:opacity-100 group-focus-within:opacity-100 transition" role="group" aria-label="Message actions"><div class="text-text-300"><div class="text-text-300 flex items-stretch justify-between"><div class="w-fit" data-state="closed"><button class="inline-flex
