ansparent [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8"><div><div class="standard-markdown grid-cols-1 grid [&amp;_&gt;_*]:min-w-0 gap-3 standard-markdown"><p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">Yes! That's <strong>autocomplete suggestions</strong> — and the split-field approach supports them, with some nuances:</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>Native browser autocomplete</strong></p>
<ul class="[li_&amp;]:mb-0 [li_&amp;]:mt-1 [li_&amp;]:gap-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ul]:pb-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ol]:pb-1 list-disc flex flex-col gap-1 pl-8 mb-3">
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Desktop Chrome and Android Chrome will cache previously entered values per field and show a dropdown if you set <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">autocomplete="on"</code> or a semantic value</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">However, because your fields are split into 3 separate inputs, the browser treats each segment independently — so it would cache <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">15</code>, <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">JAN</code>, <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">2024</code> separately, not the full date as one unit</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">On iOS Safari, autocomplete on custom fields is less reliable</li>
</ul>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>The problem with split fields + autocomplete</strong></p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">A user who previously entered <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">15-JAN-2024</code> would see suggestions like <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">15</code> in field 1, but that's ambiguous — it could have come from any 2-digit field. The browser has no way to know to suggest <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">15</code> → <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">JAN</code> → <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">2024</code> as a coordinated set.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>Better approaches for "chips" (cached value suggestions)</strong></p>
<ol class="[li_&amp;]:mb-0 [li_&amp;]:mt-1 [li_&amp;]:gap-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ul]:pb-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ol]:pb-1 list-decimal flex flex-col gap-1 pl-8 mb-3">
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2"><strong>Custom JavaScript autocomplete</strong> — Store previously entered full values (e.g., <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">15-JAN-2024</code>) in <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">localStorage</code>, then show them as tappable chips above or below the field. On tap, split and populate all three segments at once. Full control, works on iOS and all browsers.</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2"><strong>Single hidden field + split display</strong> — The three visible inputs are just for UX/keyboard purposes, but a hidden <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">&lt;input&gt;</code> holds the full combined value. The browser caches the hidden field, and you can intercept autocomplete to populate the segments.</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2"><strong><code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">datalist</code> element</strong> — You can attach a <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">&lt;datalist&gt;</code> to a field with pre-defined or previously used options as tappable suggestions. Works on desktop Chrome well, iOS support is partial.</li>
</ol>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>The most robust solution</strong> is option 1 — custom chips stored in <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">localStorage</code>. It works identically everywhere and gives you full control over the chip UI.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">Want me to build a demo with split fields + tappable history chips?</p></div></div></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-start opacity-0 group-hover:opacity-100 group-focus-within:opacity-100 transition" role="group" aria-label="Message actions"><div class="text-text-300"><div class="text-text-300 flex items-stretch justify-between"><div class="w-fit" data-state="closed"><button class="inline-flex
