ansparent [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8"><div><div class="standard-markdown grid-cols-1 grid [&amp;_&gt;_*]:min-w-0 gap-3 standard-markdown"><p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">Great idea. The address is really two parts — the street number (always numeric) and the street name (mostly alpha, but with exceptions like "2nd Ave" or "4th Street").</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">Here's the smartest approach:</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>Split into two segments:</strong></p>
<ul class="[li_&amp;]:mb-0 [li_&amp;]:mt-1 [li_&amp;]:gap-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ul]:pb-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ol]:pb-1 list-disc flex flex-col gap-1 pl-8 mb-3">
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2"><strong>Street number</strong> — <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">inputmode="numeric"</code>, short box (e.g. <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">123</code>)</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2"><strong>Street name</strong> — <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">inputmode="text"</code>, wide box, but we allow digits too (no filtering), so the user can freely type <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">2nd Ave</code> or <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">14th Street</code> without being blocked</li>
</ul>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">The street name box won't <em>force</em> alpha — it just <em>starts</em> in text/alpha keyboard mode on iOS. The user can switch to numeric mid-word if needed (as they would for "2nd"), which is the natural behaviour — we just don't get in their way.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>Optionally add a third segment for unit/apt:</strong></p>
<ul class="[li_&amp;]:mb-0 [li_&amp;]:mt-1 [li_&amp;]:gap-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ul]:pb-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ol]:pb-1 list-disc flex flex-col gap-1 pl-8 mb-3">
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">A small optional box for <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">Apt</code>, <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">Suite</code>, <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">Unit</code> etc. — also free text</li>
</ul>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">This mirrors how address forms work on apps like Google Maps and Apple Wallet, which is familiar to users.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">Want me to also add <strong>City</strong> and <strong>Province</strong> fields while I'm at it? That would complete the address block naturally — and province could be a dropdown (no keyboard needed at all), which is a nice UX touch on mobile.</p></div></div></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-start opacity-0 group-hover:opacity-100 group-focus-within:opacity-100 transition" role="group" aria-label="Message actions"><div class="text-text-300"><div class="text-text-300 flex items-stretch justify-between"><div class="w-fit" data-state="closed"><button class="inline-flex
