<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">The engine does <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">fetch('form.json')</code>, parses it, and builds the form. <strong>One important caveat:</strong> browsers block <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">fetch()</code> when you open a file directly from your desktop (the <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">file://</code> protocol). But since you're putting this on a web server, that's not an issue — it works perfectly over <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">http://</code> or <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">https://</code>.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">You'd end up with two files on your server:</p>
