ansparent [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8"><div><div class="standard-markdown grid-cols-1 grid [&amp;_&gt;_*]:min-w-0 gap-3 standard-markdown"><p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">That's a brilliant idea and yes, absolutely possible. The concept would be:</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>You design the form layout in Word</strong> — field labels, order, types, formatting — and then either:</p>
<ol class="[li_&amp;]:mb-0 [li_&amp;]:mt-1 [li_&amp;]:gap-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ul]:pb-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ol]:pb-1 list-decimal flex flex-col gap-1 pl-8 mb-3">
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2"><strong>You describe it to me</strong> and I generate the <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">form.json</code> from your description, or</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2"><strong>You upload the Word doc</strong> and I read it and generate <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">form.json</code> automatically</li>
</ol>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">Either way, <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">form.json</code> is the bridge between your Word design and the live web form. Word is a great tool for this because non-technical people are comfortable in it, you can share it with colleagues for review, and it gives you a paper version of the form at the same time.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>The cleanest workflow would be:</strong></p>
