ansparent [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8"><div><div class="standard-markdown grid-cols-1 grid [&amp;_&gt;_*]:min-w-0 gap-3 standard-markdown"><p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">Yes, absolutely possible. The idea would be:</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>You give me the URL of the existing form</strong> and I fetch it, read all the fields, and automatically generate a <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">form.json</code> that recreates it — but with all the smart keyboard switching, auto-advance, validation, and chip history built in.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">For example you'd say:</p>
<blockquote class="ml-2 border-l-4 border-border-300/10 pl-4 text-text-300">
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">"Here's the form I want to convert: <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">https://somesite.com/registration</code>"</p>
</blockquote>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">And I would:</p>
<ol class="[li_&amp;]:mb-0 [li_&amp;]:mt-1 [li_&amp;]:gap-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ul]:pb-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ol]:pb-1 list-decimal flex flex-col gap-1 pl-8 mb-3">
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Fetch the page and read all the input fields</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Identify each field's label and type</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Guess the appropriate pattern (e.g. a phone number field → <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">NNN NNN NNNN</code>)</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Generate a ready-to-upload <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">form.json</code></li>
</ol>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>The main limitation</strong> is that some websites block external fetching — in that case I couldn't read the page automatically. But you could get around that by:</p>
<ul class="[li_&amp;]:mb-0 [li_&amp;]:mt-1 [li_&amp;]:gap-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ul]:pb-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ol]:pb-1 list-disc flex flex-col gap-1 pl-8 mb-3">
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Copying the form fields into a simple table (like you've been doing) and pasting it here</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Or taking a screenshot of the form and uploading it — I could read the fields visually and generate <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">form.json</code> from the image</li>
</ul>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>The bigger picture</strong> is that this could become a very useful tool — take any paper form, PDF, or web form, describe it or show it to me, and get back a smart mobile-friendly version in minutes.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">Want to try it on an existing form right now?</p></div></div></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-start opacity-0 group-hover:opacity-100 group-focus-within:opacity-100 transition" role="group" aria-label="Message actions"><div class="text-text-300"><div class="text-text-300 flex items-stretch justify-between"><div class="w-fit" data-state="closed"><button class="inline-flex
