ansparent [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8"><div><div class="standard-markdown grid-cols-1 grid [&amp;_&gt;_*]:min-w-0 gap-3 standard-markdown"><p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">Yes — when you click the download link, instead of just clicking it, do this:</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>On Mac:</strong></p>
<ul class="[li_&amp;]:mb-0 [li_&amp;]:mt-1 [li_&amp;]:gap-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ul]:pb-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ol]:pb-1 list-disc flex flex-col gap-1 pl-8 mb-3">
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2"><strong>Right-click</strong> (or Control-click) the download link</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Choose <strong>"Save Link As…"</strong> or <strong>"Download Linked File As…"</strong></li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">A save dialog appears — navigate to whatever folder you want on your desktop or anywhere else</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Click <strong>Save</strong></li>
</ul>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">That works in both Chrome and Safari.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>Even easier — create a dedicated folder first:</strong></p>
<ol class="[li_&amp;]:mb-0 [li_&amp;]:mt-1 [li_&amp;]:gap-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ul]:pb-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ol]:pb-1 list-decimal flex flex-col gap-1 pl-8 mb-3">
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">On your Desktop, right-click and choose <strong>New Folder</strong></li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Name it something like <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">BridgeClub</code> or <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">GithubForms</code></li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">When downloading, save directly into that folder</li>
</ol>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">That way all your <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">index.html</code>, <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">form.json</code>, <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">theme.json</code> and image files stay together in one place, which also makes it easier to drag them all at once when uploading to GitHub.</p></div></div></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-start opacity-0 group-hover:opacity-100 group-focus-within:opacity-100 transition" role="group" aria-label="Message actions"><div class="text-text-300"><div class="text-text-300 flex items-stretch justify-between"><div class="w-fit" data-state="closed"><button class="inline-flex
