ansparent [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8"><div><div class="standard-markdown grid-cols-1 grid [&amp;_&gt;_*]:min-w-0 gap-3 standard-markdown"><p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">That's Safari saving the page as a complete webpage (HTML + all its assets) instead of just the file. Here's the fix:</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>In Safari:</strong></p>
<ol class="[li_&amp;]:mb-0 [li_&amp;]:mt-1 [li_&amp;]:gap-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ul]:pb-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ol]:pb-1 list-decimal flex flex-col gap-1 pl-8 mb-3">
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Right-click the download link</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Choose <strong>"Download Linked File As…"</strong> ← this is the Safari-specific wording</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Navigate to your folder and save</li>
</ol>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">If you don't see that option, try this instead:</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>Switch to Chrome for downloading:</strong>
Chrome's download behaviour is more predictable. When you click a download link in Chrome it goes straight to a single clean file — no extra folders or assets.</p>
<ol class="[li_&amp;]:mb-0 [li_&amp;]:mt-1 [li_&amp;]:gap-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ul]:pb-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ol]:pb-1 list-decimal flex flex-col gap-1 pl-8 mb-3">
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Open this conversation in Chrome</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Click the download link</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">It saves as a single file to Downloads</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2">Then move it to your folder</li>
</ol>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>Or the simplest fix</strong> — when Safari saves a messy folder, just look inside it and find the one file you actually need (<code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">form.json</code> or <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">index.html</code>) and drag just that file to your GitHub folder. Ignore everything else Safari created.</p>
